summary:
U.S., Israel and Iran agreed to a two-week ceasefire after Iran's 10-point proposal, just before U.S. President-elect Trump's deadline to reopen the Strait of Hormuz. This follows Israeli strikes yesterday on a Tehran residential area and synagogue amid renewed U.S. threats to Iran. The agreement affects global shipping and energy markets, with oil prices dropping 15 percent. Talks are expected next to avert wider war.

In eastern Congo, Rwanda-backed rebels overran Congolese troops and entered Goma, the region's main aid hub, with gunfire reported and over one million people displaced inside the city. The U.N. warned of a humanitarian crisis threatening aid operations and regional stability. Separately, Ukraine increased strikes on Russian oil refineries and shipping to reduce Moscow's war revenue, which rose amid tensions over Iran. UK Prime Minister Keir Starmer told a virtual coalition of leaders excluding the U.S. that Russia must engage in Ukraine ceasefire talks to end the three-year war.

Israel allowed thousands of displaced Palestinians to cross a bisecting military zone into northern Gaza after a hostage release impasse ended. SpaceX launched Crew-10 on a Falcon 9 from Florida with NASA astronauts Anne McClain and Nichole Ayers, Japan's Takuya Onishi, and Russia's Kirill Peskov to the ISS, enabling the return of stuck astronauts Wilmore and Williams after nine months and restoring normal rotations. North Korea fired several short-range missiles into the sea from its east coast after South Korea ridiculed inter-Korean ties. Rex Heuermann, charged in the Long Island Gilgo Beach serial killings, agreed to plead guilty on Wednesday. NATO deployed its first coordinated response after a second deep-sea cable cut in the Baltic Sea."}
